-- Japan, China, Indonesia, Thailand, Korea: Asia Bonds, Currency Preview
-- B y   A n d r e a   W o n g
-- 2010-09-30T23:06:28Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-30/japan-china-indonesia-thailand-korea-asia-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  and Finance
Minister Yoshihiko Noda will hold media briefings after a
Cabinet meeting in the morning. Sengoku will have another press
briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  The statistics bureau will release at 8:30 a.m. in Tokyo
August reports on the jobless rate, household spending and
consumer prices.  The yield on the 1 percent government bond due September
2020 was at 0.930 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co.,
the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 83.58 per dollar at 7:57 a.m. in Tokyo.  China: The purchasing managers’ index for manufacturing
rose to 52.5 in September from 51.7 last month, data will show
today, according to the median estimate of economists in a
Bloomberg survey.  The yield on the 2.53 percent note due June 2015 was 2.65
percent. The yuan was at 6.6901.  South Korea: The government will release its consumer price
index and export figures for September today. Inflation was 2.9
percent last month compared to 2.6 percent a month earlier,
according to a Bloomberg survey of economists. A separate
Bloomberg survey showed exports rose 15.7 percent last month
from a year earlier, slowing from 29.6 percent growth in August.  The yield on the 3.75 percent debt due June 2013 was 3.34
percent, according to Korea Stock Exchange. The won traded at
1,140.20.  Indonesia: Consumer prices rose 5.94 percent from a year
earlier in September after an increase of 6.44 percent in the
previous month, economists forecast in a Bloomberg survey ahead
of data to be released today. Export growth may have slowed to
20 percent in August from a year earlier after a 29 percent
advance in July, another Bloomberg survey showed.  The yield on the 11 percent government note due November
2020 was 7.66 percent, according to the Inter Dealer Market
Association. The rupiah was at 8,915.  Thailand: Consumer prices rose 3.3 percent in September
from a year earlier, the same pace as in August, according to
the median forecast in a Bloomberg survey before today’s data.  Foreign-exchange reserves data for the week through Sept.
24 is due today. Reserves increased 1 percent to $159.1 billion
in the previous week.  The central bank will sell 80 billion baht ($2.6 billion)
of 14-day bills.  The yield on the 5.85 percent note maturing March 2021 was
3.15 percent. The baht was at 30.36.  India: India will sell 110 billion rupees ($2.4 billion) of
five-, 12-, and 17-year bonds today.  The yield on the 7.84 percent bond due May 2020 was 7.85
percent. The rupee was at 44.94.  To contact the reporter on this story:
